So if you go on GitHub, I'm Topepo.

00:01:03.919 --> 00:01:06.320
And you'll find right up top of the repositories

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:10.760
this 2025, oops, NYR.

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:12.720
Forgive me.

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:18.519
All right, so we pose some question or questions to LLMs.

00:01:18.519 --> 00:01:19.760
They're constantly changing.

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:21.480
There's plenty of vendors.

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:23.919
With the same vendor at the same time, queried a few times,

00:01:23.919 --> 00:01:26.199
you can get different results.

00:01:26.199 --> 00:01:29.919
A lot of times, we hope to try to measure which one's

00:01:29.919 --> 00:01:31.800
working best for us.

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:33.879
If you're a developer or something like that,

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:35.800
hopefully a qualitative or a quantitative way

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:38.080
to measure if I'm developing a prompt,

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:40.680
is it getting any better, am I making it worse?

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:43.639
So we basically want to have results.

00:01:43.639 --> 00:01:45.720
And I'm here to talk about the ways

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:48.680
we can analyze those results.

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:51.440
So this is with Simon Couch, who used to be in the Tiny Models

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:52.279
group working for me.

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:57.080
And he's been so adept at making really good small-scale AI

00:01:57.080 --> 00:02:00.160
tools in R that he's in our new AI group.

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:04.919
But he wrote a post yesterday about something very much

00:02:04.919 --> 00:02:07.760
related to this, where he's working on an assistant

00:02:07.760 --> 00:02:09.320
for Tiny Models.

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:12.800
And he was doing all this work to get the LLMs to recognize

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:16.199
the right syntax for Tiny Models and did a lot of work for that.

00:02:16.199 --> 00:02:18.039
And then all the new models came out,

00:02:18.039 --> 00:02:20.240
and they just worked better without all the work

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:21.639
he had previously done.

00:02:21.639 --> 00:02:23.240
And it just seemed like a good example.

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:24.720
It's an interesting read.

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:28.880
It's a good example, though, because there's so much not

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:32.199
volatility so much as it's very dynamic.

00:02:32.199 --> 00:02:34.479
It'd be nice to have a way to measure effectiveness.

00:02:34.479 --> 00:02:36.720
And so hopefully, one thing we'll eventually get to

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:39.000
is something where we can just say,

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.320
we have some leader LLM from the last time we looked at things.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:45.119
And then we have a set of questions that we want to pose.

00:02:45.119 --> 00:02:48.440
And we can just turn that loose and measure.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:51.039
I have it written as LLM or model here,

00:02:51.039 --> 00:02:52.679
but it's a combination of your prompt

00:02:52.679 --> 00:02:55.759
or whether you're using RAG or MCP or something like that.

00:02:55.759 --> 00:02:59.199
However, you get the system working.

00:02:59.199 --> 00:03:04.199
And hopefully, you can measure some inferentially,

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:06.220
say something about the difference in accuracy

00:03:06.220 --> 00:03:07.919
between these models.

00:03:07.919 --> 00:03:10.679
That's what we hope to get to.

00:03:10.679 --> 00:03:14.080
So I thought I'd mention two things, inspect and vitals.

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:18.020
Inspect is a Python-based framework that the UK created.

00:03:18.020 --> 00:03:20.399
I have to be honest, the only reason I'm familiar with it

00:03:20.399 --> 00:03:22.399
is because the person who owns our company

00:03:22.399 --> 00:03:24.880
just went off to the UK and just worked on it

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:26.479
for a long time.

00:03:26.479 --> 00:03:29.960
And so it's kind of an amazing feat of engineering.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:32.119
It's built for very, very large-scale stuff.

00:03:32.119 --> 00:03:35.380
It can handle crazy, agentic stuff

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:38.520
that large companies would make.

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:40.360
But it's a little bit overkill if you're just

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:42.479
like somebody who's doing package development,

00:03:42.479 --> 00:03:45.399
especially in R, and you want to just measure these things.

00:03:45.399 --> 00:03:47.399
So Simon created this package called vitals.

00:03:47.399 --> 00:03:50.160
And it takes a little bit of inspect.

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:53.399
And it basically, I don't know if he would say it this way,

00:03:53.399 --> 00:03:56.940
but I think of it as like unit tests for LLMs.

00:03:56.940 --> 00:04:00.080
So you write a list of questions that you want to continually,

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:02.240
like you can expand them, but they're

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:05.559
like a static set of questions you want to answer and see,

00:04:05.559 --> 00:04:08.399
are these models better at this corpus of questions?

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:10.119
So it's almost like a unit test.

00:04:10.119 --> 00:04:12.320
And so the example we're using is not a new one.

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:14.360
You can tell by the models that are listed there.

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:17.380
But there's 25 questions related to R. Some of them

00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:20.380
are like R6, or tidyverse, or base IR questions,

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:22.179
or fairly diverse.

00:04:22.179 --> 00:04:28.779
And then Simon ran them within vitals using GPT 4.1, Gemini 2.5,

00:04:28.779 --> 00:04:30.220
and CloudForce on it.

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:33.059
And then we know that a lot of these models are stochastic.

00:04:33.059 --> 00:04:34.619
So if you run them more than once,

00:04:34.619 --> 00:04:35.820
you'll get different answers.

00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:37.980
So for each one, like vitals that you do this,

00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:39.899
you just say measure it three times,

00:04:39.899 --> 00:04:41.480
or however many you want to look at it.

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:45.140
So he did each for three repeats of those.

00:04:45.140 --> 00:04:48.140
So we have 25 things measured over three models,

00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:50.579
three times each.

00:04:50.579 --> 00:04:51.940
And just a little bit of notation

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:55.339
and thought about the data, we decided to,

00:04:55.339 --> 00:04:57.739
these are fairly small-scope questions.

00:04:57.739 --> 00:05:01.339
So we can programmatically rate them, basically.

00:05:01.339 --> 00:05:04.380
And I'm going to basically punt on all of the different ways

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:06.839
you might be able to take the output of LLMs

00:05:06.839 --> 00:05:08.500
and measure them in terms of correctness.

00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:10.299
Bill talked about that yesterday.

00:05:10.299 --> 00:05:12.579
But we could very easily say that things

00:05:12.579 --> 00:05:15.339
were either correct, partially correct, or correct.

00:05:15.339 --> 00:05:17.339
And partially correct could mean like it gave me,

00:05:17.339 --> 00:05:20.299
I asked it to do a GM smooth, and it did it well.

00:05:20.299 --> 00:05:22.579
But then it hallucinated a link to the documentation

00:05:22.579 --> 00:05:24.100
or something like that.

00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:27.000
It did a decent job, but not quite all the way there.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:28.540
So there's a little bit of notation.

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:31.119
I'll show you an equation in a minute where this will matter.

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:33.739
We have C equal three outcome levels, so like incorrect,

00:05:33.739 --> 00:05:35.299
partially correct, and so on.

00:05:35.299 --> 00:05:37.540
Three LLMs, so that's P equal three.

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:40.579
And so I'm going to use the term epochs for replicates.

00:05:40.579 --> 00:05:42.200
So if we run each of these three times,

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:43.640
it's like three epochs.

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:45.600
And I'll be talking about these ordinal outcomes

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:47.799
as like the thing we're trying to measure.

00:05:47.799 --> 00:05:51.959
But really, this is not the most complicated model in the world.

00:05:51.959 --> 00:05:54.399
But if you were doing something like binary outcomes

00:05:54.399 --> 00:05:57.640
or proportion correct or even like some number system,

00:05:57.640 --> 00:05:59.480
the model gets actually a lot more simpler

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:01.239
than the one I'll show you in a minute.

00:06:01.239 --> 00:06:03.480
So the system that I'm going to talk about here

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:06.160
can work on pretty much anything.

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:07.820
Here's like a visualization of the data.

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:09.920
You can see the questions on the y-axis,

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:12.440
and we've just color-coded the answers.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:16.200
You can see when I inspect this with my eyeballs,

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:19.440
I think it's maybe like 40%, 50% correct just

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:21.880
based on the colors.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:23.880
That's my visual assessment of it.

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:27.200
But you can see some go from like completely correct

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:30.079
to completely incorrect or in between partially correct

00:06:30.079 --> 00:06:30.559
or not.

00:06:30.559 --> 00:06:32.799
And then some of them on the top and bottom

00:06:32.799 --> 00:06:36.440
are pretty consistently good or bad.

00:06:36.440 --> 00:06:40.040
So last year, somebody from Anthropic

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:45.200
released a manuscript on rating LLMs, statistical approaches

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:45.839
for doing that.

00:06:45.839 --> 00:06:49.600
And it's actually a quite good manuscript,

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:51.140
especially in terms of the spirit

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:53.119
of what it's trying to do.

00:06:53.119 --> 00:06:55.040
And so it's talking about if you measure

00:06:55.040 --> 00:06:56.579
these things multiple times, you have

00:06:56.579 --> 00:07:00.239
to account for the within question correlation.

00:07:00.239 --> 00:07:02.239
And a lot of the ideas are good.

00:07:02.239 --> 00:07:04.239
The part that kind of stood out for me is then

00:07:04.239 --> 00:07:06.359
they went into details on how to do it.

00:07:07.359 --> 00:07:11.880
It's not wrong, but it's not especially good methodology.

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:14.480
It's also the situation where for different experimental

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:17.079
designs, you would have different equations.

00:07:17.079 --> 00:07:19.320
And as a statistician, we'd never think about that.

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:24.160
So I'll talk about a more top level way that can compensate

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:25.920
and not have to really think about the,

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:28.119
like it won't be deriving equations for these things.

00:07:28.119 --> 00:07:29.359
It's already done for you.

00:07:29.359 --> 00:07:31.399
And the methods are very versatile,

00:07:31.399 --> 00:07:35.600
and they can work for pretty much any experimental design.

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:37.160
And I'm a person who's mostly focused

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:40.559
on estimation problems my whole career,

00:07:40.559 --> 00:07:43.160
and machine learning, and I'm a statistician,

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:44.480
so for me to stand up here and say,

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:48.079
we need statistical inference is kind of a change for me.

00:07:48.079 --> 00:07:49.760
But that's what we need.

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:53.380
And basically, standard kind of things

00:07:53.380 --> 00:07:54.559
are what we really need here.

00:07:54.559 --> 00:07:55.799
These problems have, believe it or not,

00:07:55.799 --> 00:07:57.320
been already solved.

00:07:57.320 --> 00:07:59.959
And so just as an example,

00:07:59.959 --> 00:08:02.739
generalized linear models are 51 years ago.

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:06.019
Like, that's crazy to me.

00:08:06.019 --> 00:08:09.140
And so a framework like that solves almost all the problems

00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:10.339
that we're working on.

00:08:10.339 --> 00:08:12.200
So although the paper is really good,

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:14.540
like their derivation of equations for this and that

00:08:14.540 --> 00:08:15.459
were really unnecessary,

00:08:15.459 --> 00:08:16.820
because we already have all these frameworks

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:18.660
to do what we want.

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:20.420
Most of the experimental designs that we would do

00:08:20.420 --> 00:08:22.100
fall into basically ANOVA models,

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:23.700
like analysis of variance.

00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:25.339
Like we have these LLMs and their groups,

00:08:25.339 --> 00:08:27.779
and we want to make comparisons between them.

00:08:27.779 --> 00:08:30.700
There might be like some sort of numerical covariate,

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:32.539
like the number of tokens or the cost

00:08:33.299 --> 00:08:34.219
that we might put in these models.

00:08:34.219 --> 00:08:36.140
But there's nothing crazy about them.

00:08:36.140 --> 00:08:38.059
And the experimental design is probably

00:08:38.059 --> 00:08:39.820
fairly balanced and complete.

00:08:39.820 --> 00:08:42.299
So they don't seem like they're hard to fit models to.

00:08:42.299 --> 00:08:44.239
So there's a lot of basic things that,

00:08:44.239 --> 00:08:45.900
at least as a statistician,

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:47.179
you would maybe get in like your first year

00:08:47.179 --> 00:08:49.539
of graduate school, if not sooner,

00:08:49.539 --> 00:08:51.539
that can handle like this design

00:08:51.539 --> 00:08:54.039
as well as other types of outcomes.

00:08:54.039 --> 00:08:56.179
So this is like really the only equation we'll see.

00:08:56.179 --> 00:08:58.219
It looks kind of daunting,

00:08:58.219 --> 00:08:59.500
but if you've ever seen the equation

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:02.260
for logistic regression, that's 2 3rds of what's here.

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:05.580
Over here on the left-hand side of the equation,

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:06.619
you basically have to load it,

00:09:06.619 --> 00:09:09.219
just like you would with logistic regression.

00:09:09.219 --> 00:09:10.940
So this is called a proportional odds model.

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:14.140
It's built for cumulative or ordinal data,

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:15.979
like ordinal outcomes, like incorrect,

00:09:15.979 --> 00:09:17.539
partially correct, correct.

00:09:17.539 --> 00:09:19.659
And so the only real difference on the left-hand side

00:09:19.659 --> 00:09:21.059
between this and logistic regression

00:09:21.059 --> 00:09:24.219
is you're modeling the probability that's cumulative.

00:09:24.219 --> 00:09:26.599
So you might, so if you have three,

00:09:26.599 --> 00:09:27.900
like we do have outcomes,

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:30.099
you build two logistic regressions.

00:09:30.099 --> 00:09:32.299
And the problem is the probabilities

00:09:32.299 --> 00:09:34.179
for partially correct, incorrect, and correct

00:09:34.179 --> 00:09:35.099
have to add up to one.

00:09:35.099 --> 00:09:36.460
So you can't fit three models

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:39.340
because there's a dependency and a constraint in there.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:41.099
So you fit two out of the three,

00:09:41.099 --> 00:09:43.020
and then you can infer the third probability

00:09:43.020 --> 00:09:44.859
from the two models.

00:09:44.859 --> 00:09:45.940
And so on the left-hand side there,

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:48.520
the logit is like a probability of being,

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:51.099
like if C here were equal to two,

00:09:51.099 --> 00:09:52.979
we would say that that's a probability

00:09:52.979 --> 00:09:55.299
of being incorrect or partially correct

00:09:55.299 --> 00:09:59.219
versus the bottom would be, in that case, being correct.

00:09:59.219 --> 00:10:00.659
So it's very much like a logit

00:10:00.659 --> 00:10:02.419
where you have like a probability on the top

00:10:02.419 --> 00:10:04.580
in the parentheses and it's opposite on the bottom

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:06.299
except for it's cumulative.

00:10:06.299 --> 00:10:08.020
And on the right-hand side here,

00:10:08.020 --> 00:10:08.859
looking at the betas,

00:10:08.859 --> 00:10:11.020
that's the same thing you would see in linear regression

00:10:11.020 --> 00:10:12.520
or logistic regression.

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:14.960
These are the things we actually care about.

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:16.739
So beta two, the way it's written here

00:10:16.739 --> 00:10:19.859
would be the difference in, let's say, accuracy

00:10:19.859 --> 00:10:21.580
between, let's say we ordered them

00:10:21.580 --> 00:10:24.200
as being chat GPT, Gemini, and Claude.

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:26.500
So beta two, there would be the estimated difference

00:10:26.500 --> 00:10:29.979
between what GPT gives you and what Gemini gives you.

00:10:29.979 --> 00:10:31.580
And the third coefficient would be the difference

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:33.659
between GPT and Claude.

00:10:34.539 --> 00:10:37.460
Now the two new things here is this theta

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:40.179
is necessary for the ordinal regression part.

00:10:40.179 --> 00:10:42.880
It's basically a intercept that is specific

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:46.260
to the level of the outcome that we're modeling.

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:48.820
And the alpha here is not necessarily needed,

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:52.140
but it is for our design because we've taken each question

00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:53.900
and we've replicated it three times.

00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:56.739
We've taken the same setting and just repeated it a bunch.

00:10:56.739 --> 00:10:59.179
And in statistics, we call that,

00:10:59.179 --> 00:11:02.400
we call the question the independent experimental unit,

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:04.419
but the rows in our dataset aren't independent

00:11:04.419 --> 00:11:06.340
because if we had the three replicates

00:11:06.340 --> 00:11:08.020
in rows one through three,

00:11:08.020 --> 00:11:09.940
those results are correlated with one another

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:11.219
and they're more like each other

00:11:11.219 --> 00:11:13.500
than they would be for any of the other rows.

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:15.979
And if you ever had a lecture about a paired t-test

00:11:15.979 --> 00:11:18.059
versus a t-test, it's the same thing.

00:11:18.059 --> 00:11:19.580
If we don't model that correlation

00:11:19.580 --> 00:11:22.539
that's sort of already baked into the data,

00:11:22.539 --> 00:11:24.219
then our standard errors are a lot higher.

00:11:24.219 --> 00:11:26.619
We've basically underpowered our whole design.

00:11:26.619 --> 00:11:28.900
And so what alpha here does is it estimates

00:11:28.900 --> 00:11:32.179
that correlation and basically factors it out.

00:11:32.179 --> 00:11:34.900
So it looks like a lot, but on the left side here

00:11:34.900 --> 00:11:36.140
and on the far right side,

00:11:36.140 --> 00:11:37.900
it's basically logistic regression.

00:11:40.219 --> 00:11:43.400
So Dr. Gellman's not here right now.

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:45.780
So I'm gonna talk about frequentist

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:47.299
and Bayesian methods for estimation

00:11:47.299 --> 00:11:49.500
and talk about them at a very high level.

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:52.020
So on the frequentist side, it's basically,

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:54.219
if you've ever used a mixed model in statistics,

00:11:54.219 --> 00:11:55.619
that's what we're talking about.

00:11:55.619 --> 00:11:56.820
It's the same model.

00:11:56.820 --> 00:11:58.179
So we're gonna be looking at this,

00:11:58.179 --> 00:12:01.260
but just different ways to estimate all these coefficients.

00:12:01.260 --> 00:12:03.380
And in the mixed model, basically all we do

00:12:03.380 --> 00:12:05.580
is we know what the likelihood is

00:12:05.580 --> 00:12:07.520
because we've written down a probability model

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:09.940
that's binomial, an ordinal binomial model

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:11.460
or multinomial model,

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:12.900
and we can write down its likelihood

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:14.780
and then we can basically optimize that

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:16.700
to find the maximum likelihood estimates.

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:18.739
It's pretty straightforward.

00:12:18.739 --> 00:12:20.539
Sometimes, like for design like this,

00:12:20.539 --> 00:12:22.460
it's pretty easy to fit.

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:24.299
The inference is pretty easy.

00:12:24.299 --> 00:12:26.140
I mean, if you're into p-values,

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:27.780
that's, you know, I'm happy for you.

00:12:27.780 --> 00:12:29.400
You could do that.

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:31.400
Confidence intervals are kind of better,

00:12:32.659 --> 00:12:34.460
but you can make inferences on these things.

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:35.940
And it's really easy to do in R.

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:37.900
There's an ordinal package.

00:12:37.900 --> 00:12:41.619
You just, one line, you have the entire model that I wrote.

00:12:41.619 --> 00:12:43.940
The only interesting things about this is this.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:47.619
This is like the standard R sort of hierarchical model

00:12:47.619 --> 00:12:50.700
formula where we're modeling these scores

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:53.780
as a function of LLM is just a factor variable,

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:56.659
an indicator for whether it's CLOD or GPT and so on.

00:12:56.659 --> 00:12:59.820
And then the parentheses one bar ID,

00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:03.539
the ID is the independent experimental unit.

00:13:03.539 --> 00:13:06.140
And then one means that we have a random intercept

00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:07.940
that is driven by that unit,

00:13:07.940 --> 00:13:11.140
and that's basically this intercept here.

00:13:11.140 --> 00:13:13.059
So, you know, this is a complicated model,

00:13:13.059 --> 00:13:15.260
but the code's like trivially easy.

00:13:15.260 --> 00:13:16.380
So once you fit this,

00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:18.820
you can get your confidence intervals and p-values.

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:21.219
One thing you might want to do is fit a null model,

00:13:21.219 --> 00:13:22.859
which assumes they're all the same,

00:13:22.859 --> 00:13:25.820
and then this would do like a likelihood ratio test

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:26.780
up front to say, like,

00:13:26.780 --> 00:13:28.539
is there any difference between these things

00:13:28.539 --> 00:13:31.179
before I try to pull out their pairwise differences?

00:13:31.179 --> 00:13:32.919
And at least from a statistical perspective,

00:13:32.919 --> 00:13:34.099
you're safe doing this

00:13:34.099 --> 00:13:37.700
before the all combinations sort of analysis.

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:39.780
But if you want to get all the p-values

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:40.739
and the confidence intervals,

00:13:40.739 --> 00:13:42.020
you run the tiny method on that,

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:44.119
and you have a nice data frame to do that.

00:13:44.119 --> 00:13:46.760
So it seems really complicated, but it's pretty easy.

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:51.159
Here's what the results look like for our dataset.

00:13:51.159 --> 00:13:53.780
And so on the left-hand side there where we have parameters,

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:56.159
that's like the logit unit estimates.

00:13:56.159 --> 00:13:59.080
So logit goes from negative infinity to infinity.

00:13:59.080 --> 00:14:02.159
Zero is like the 50% mark in the transformation.

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:04.000
So when you look at the Gemini results,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.280
the estimate is fairly low.

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:08.640
You can look at the confidence interval next to the p-value

00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:11.619
and pretty easily say that there's really no difference

00:14:11.659 --> 00:14:14.500
between CHA2GPT results and the Gemini results

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:17.140
for this particular analysis.

00:14:17.140 --> 00:14:19.020
And then you get to the CLOD results.

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:22.380
The parameter estimate's a lot higher,

00:14:22.380 --> 00:14:26.640
and the confidence interval barely covers zero.

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:28.260
But from a statistical perspective,

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:31.539
we say that a 0.5 estimate on logit scale

00:14:31.539 --> 00:14:33.539
is a pretty significant number,

00:14:33.539 --> 00:14:35.840
but it's not really statistically significant.

00:14:35.840 --> 00:14:38.739
There's not enough evidence to say it's different from zero.

00:14:39.619 --> 00:14:41.739
And also we can convert these to odds ratios

00:14:41.739 --> 00:14:43.179
if that's better for you.

00:14:43.179 --> 00:14:45.940
So the odds ratio here, sort of the null value is one.

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:47.419
That would mean they're equal.

00:14:47.419 --> 00:14:52.419
And 1.73 means there's about a 73% improvement

00:14:53.419 --> 00:14:55.940
of using CLOD for this dataset over GPT,

00:14:55.940 --> 00:14:59.140
but that's not really statistically significant here.

00:14:59.140 --> 00:15:01.140
And speaking of statistical significance,

00:15:02.099 --> 00:15:04.659
I find just having to write out,

00:15:04.659 --> 00:15:06.659
because I used to have to do this in previous jobs,

00:15:06.700 --> 00:15:08.900
what it means to be a confidence interval

00:15:08.900 --> 00:15:10.820
just kills me every time.

00:15:10.820 --> 00:15:14.539
It's like this circuitous, almost terrible way

00:15:14.539 --> 00:15:17.599
to explain to somebody officially what this means.

00:15:17.599 --> 00:15:20.219
Like if you did it a bunch of times,

00:15:20.219 --> 00:15:21.539
or 95% of the times,

00:15:21.539 --> 00:15:23.580
the true value would fall between these intervals,

00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:25.219
and that's, ugh.

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:28.559
But that's frequentist methods for you.

00:15:29.719 --> 00:15:30.900
One cool thing about these models

00:15:30.900 --> 00:15:32.979
is you can get estimates of difficulty.

00:15:32.979 --> 00:15:35.419
So these are the intercept estimates

00:15:35.419 --> 00:15:37.659
for the actual questions.

00:15:37.659 --> 00:15:38.739
So what we can do is,

00:15:38.739 --> 00:15:40.419
you can imagine if you had like 500

00:15:40.419 --> 00:15:41.940
or thousands of questions,

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:44.599
you can really easily use a good statistical method

00:15:44.599 --> 00:15:45.859
to rank them in terms of like,

00:15:45.859 --> 00:15:48.260
well, which ones did it just not do well on?

00:15:48.260 --> 00:15:50.599
And then adjust your prop accordingly.

00:15:50.599 --> 00:15:52.539
So we have a few here that you got all right,

00:15:52.539 --> 00:15:54.960
and they're sort of like hitting the top of the scale.

00:15:54.960 --> 00:15:55.799
With this model,

00:15:55.799 --> 00:15:58.179
this is sort of constrained to be a normal distribution.

00:15:58.179 --> 00:16:01.479
So they sort of fall under a normality type situation.

00:16:01.479 --> 00:16:03.820
And then we have especially like three down here

00:16:03.820 --> 00:16:06.580
that just weren't answered at all well.

00:16:06.580 --> 00:16:07.739
Some of these are like,

00:16:07.739 --> 00:16:10.260
zero would be like average difficulty.

00:16:11.299 --> 00:16:15.059
And so that's one thing you can get out of these models.

00:16:15.059 --> 00:16:16.940
So that's just like a summary of the frequentist methods.

00:16:16.940 --> 00:16:18.979
Now we move to the Bayesian methods.

00:16:18.979 --> 00:16:20.780
And like Dr. Gilman was talking about,

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:22.380
you put priors on your parameters,

00:16:22.380 --> 00:16:23.659
and they express your belief

00:16:23.659 --> 00:16:26.039
about what they could possibly be.

00:16:26.039 --> 00:16:28.260
And most Bayesian models have pretty good

00:16:29.299 --> 00:16:31.380
prior distribution defaults,

00:16:31.380 --> 00:16:32.280
and you can use those.

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:33.580
They're very vague,

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:36.460
which means they're designed to,

00:16:37.340 --> 00:16:38.859
especially when there's a fair amount of data,

00:16:38.859 --> 00:16:40.940
let the data speak more to the parameter estimates

00:16:40.940 --> 00:16:42.659
than the prior.

00:16:42.659 --> 00:16:45.460
And so the defaults are pretty good.

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:47.460
If you don't know what your prior is,

00:16:47.460 --> 00:16:49.260
I'll show you in a second,

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:51.659
one that I changed from the default.

00:16:51.659 --> 00:16:52.619
But you would estimate this

00:16:52.619 --> 00:16:54.539
with Markov chain and Monte Carlo,

00:16:54.539 --> 00:16:56.580
which is quite a feat sometimes.

00:16:56.580 --> 00:16:59.940
It takes a little bit to evaluate and run,

00:16:59.940 --> 00:17:02.900
even with a design that's pretty small like this.

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:06.060
But the work you have to do to make a prior

00:17:06.060 --> 00:17:09.199
and do MCMC, it's not trivial, but it's workable,

00:17:09.199 --> 00:17:12.260
but it's way worth it when you get to the inference stage.

00:17:12.260 --> 00:17:13.819
Because inference of Bayesian models

00:17:13.819 --> 00:17:16.739
is comparatively delightful,

00:17:16.739 --> 00:17:19.140
if I ever felt that way about inference.

00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:20.739
It's just really easy to do.

00:17:21.699 --> 00:17:23.300
If you want to fit this model,

00:17:23.300 --> 00:17:25.180
you can use the BRMS package.

00:17:25.180 --> 00:17:28.859
You use, R has a standard formula method

00:17:28.859 --> 00:17:29.699
for this type of thing,

00:17:29.699 --> 00:17:32.140
so we just recycle our formula.

00:17:32.140 --> 00:17:33.540
The main thing is right here,

00:17:33.540 --> 00:17:36.339
we choose a logit model with a cumulative link.

00:17:36.339 --> 00:17:37.540
That was the left-hand side

00:17:37.540 --> 00:17:39.260
of the equation I showed you earlier.

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:41.079
And then one thing I did was,

00:17:41.079 --> 00:17:43.060
I wanted to take the prior for the intercepts

00:17:43.060 --> 00:17:44.500
that are due to our questions,

00:17:44.500 --> 00:17:47.540
and give them a very heavy tail distribution.

00:17:47.540 --> 00:17:49.540
So this is sort of like a normal distribution,

00:17:49.540 --> 00:17:51.660
but the tails, the extremes of the distribution

00:17:51.660 --> 00:17:53.020
have more mass in them.

00:17:53.020 --> 00:17:55.219
And the reason I chose that is because

00:17:55.219 --> 00:17:57.579
you can imagine some questions that you give it

00:17:57.579 --> 00:17:59.579
that would be extraordinarily difficult

00:17:59.579 --> 00:18:01.380
or extraordinarily easy.

00:18:01.380 --> 00:18:02.500
And with a normal distribution,

00:18:02.500 --> 00:18:06.699
it sort of enforces that probability range.

00:18:06.699 --> 00:18:09.099
And so a t-distribution would allow you to estimate

00:18:09.099 --> 00:18:12.099
what the normal would be considered outliers

00:18:12.099 --> 00:18:14.060
in terms of difficulty or easiness

00:18:14.060 --> 00:18:15.619
in terms of their questions.

00:18:15.619 --> 00:18:18.579
So it's just a different way to think about

00:18:18.579 --> 00:18:20.900
what you would expect from your questions.

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:22.680
And then you can add all the options you want.

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:24.219
There's things like how many chains,

00:18:24.219 --> 00:18:25.979
how many iterations, and so on.

00:18:26.819 --> 00:18:30.619
And so there's a lot here to do with the Bayesian models,

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:32.420
but it works very well.

00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:35.420
And the results here are,

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:38.140
because I didn't really change the default priors,

00:18:38.140 --> 00:18:39.660
it's a pretty stable model,

00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:41.140
these results are pretty close

00:18:41.140 --> 00:18:43.739
to what we got with the frequentist model.

00:18:43.739 --> 00:18:46.459
You'll notice it says like five percentile, 95 percentile.

00:18:46.459 --> 00:18:48.099
These are credible intervals.

00:18:48.099 --> 00:18:49.260
So one thing that's different

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:51.699
when you fit a model with maximum likelihood,

00:18:51.699 --> 00:18:53.780
your parameters take on a single value.

00:18:53.780 --> 00:18:56.300
They're the best parameters that explain your data.

00:18:56.300 --> 00:18:57.260
And with Bayesian methods,

00:18:57.260 --> 00:18:58.739
what you get is you get a distribution

00:18:58.739 --> 00:18:59.900
around your parameters at the end.

00:18:59.979 --> 00:19:01.819
You get a posterior distribution.

00:19:01.819 --> 00:19:03.780
And what that is is the probability distribution

00:19:03.780 --> 00:19:05.180
around your parameters.

00:19:05.180 --> 00:19:07.140
And typically when we want to summarize,

00:19:07.140 --> 00:19:09.979
I'm going to use the mean or the mode or the distribution.

00:19:09.979 --> 00:19:13.099
So the means here are pretty close to what we got before.

00:19:13.099 --> 00:19:14.500
And then instead of a confidence interval

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:18.099
or credible intervals, we just take some,

00:19:18.099 --> 00:19:19.180
well, the easiest thing to do,

00:19:19.180 --> 00:19:20.739
some quantiles of that distribution

00:19:20.739 --> 00:19:23.739
to give us a sense of the variability around things.

00:19:23.739 --> 00:19:26.380
And then again, with maximum likelihood estimation

00:19:26.380 --> 00:19:29.339
and Bayesian results, the nature of those models

00:19:29.699 --> 00:19:30.939
and their properties allow us,

00:19:30.939 --> 00:19:32.540
when we do the odds ratios,

00:19:32.540 --> 00:19:35.020
we're just exponentiating the parameter estimates

00:19:35.020 --> 00:19:37.099
and their distributions or intervals.

00:19:37.099 --> 00:19:39.180
And so this is basically how it works.

00:19:39.180 --> 00:19:40.819
But it's remarkably similar to what we got

00:19:40.819 --> 00:19:43.339
on the frequentist side.

00:19:43.339 --> 00:19:44.180
So you might think like,

00:19:44.180 --> 00:19:45.979
well, why would I go all the trouble of doing that?

00:19:45.979 --> 00:19:47.459
And here's where the answer is.

00:19:47.459 --> 00:19:49.459
The inference is incredibly simple.

00:19:49.459 --> 00:19:51.380
Instead of talking about like if we repeat this

00:19:51.380 --> 00:19:52.420
and blah, blah, blah,

00:19:52.420 --> 00:19:54.219
I can look at the posterior distribution,

00:19:54.219 --> 00:19:57.020
let's say for the Claude parameter estimate

00:19:57.020 --> 00:19:59.380
and say like how much of that distribution

00:19:59.380 --> 00:20:01.540
is positive compared to zero.

00:20:01.540 --> 00:20:03.859
And when I do that for this particular experiment,

00:20:03.859 --> 00:20:08.180
92% probability that Claude four is better than GPT four.

00:20:08.180 --> 00:20:10.339
It's a really direct statement.

00:20:10.339 --> 00:20:11.939
It also seems a lot more emphatic

00:20:11.939 --> 00:20:14.380
than we got with the frequentist analysis

00:20:14.380 --> 00:20:16.339
because the frequentist analysis hides behind

00:20:16.339 --> 00:20:18.619
a sort of arbitrary decision

00:20:18.619 --> 00:20:22.140
and give you some like indirect ways of saying

00:20:22.140 --> 00:20:23.979
how true that situation is.

00:20:23.979 --> 00:20:26.540
And this is delightful to use

00:20:27.020 --> 00:20:28.699
when you have to explain things to people

00:20:28.699 --> 00:20:31.619
because it's a very direct way to look at,

00:20:32.540 --> 00:20:34.459
it's not, I don't want to call it significance,

00:20:34.459 --> 00:20:37.979
but how likely it is to be better than the alternative.

00:20:40.500 --> 00:20:42.699
And so we also get the difficulty estimates.

00:20:44.099 --> 00:20:46.819
So the nice thing about this is since the Bayesian model

00:20:46.819 --> 00:20:49.579
is we can put credible intervals around them

00:20:49.579 --> 00:20:51.540
and get some sense of their variation,

00:20:51.540 --> 00:20:52.459
which is kind of nice too.

00:20:52.459 --> 00:20:53.979
If you're looking for like,

00:20:53.979 --> 00:20:57.540
what seems to be conclusively difficult questions,

00:20:57.540 --> 00:20:59.660
you can get that by using these intervals.

00:21:02.219 --> 00:21:04.979
So I mean, I think one of the conclusions I have,

00:21:04.979 --> 00:21:07.619
and this talk is not like a reaction to that paper,

00:21:07.619 --> 00:21:09.260
but it did make me think a lot

00:21:09.260 --> 00:21:12.300
that even in a company like Anthropic,

00:21:12.300 --> 00:21:15.140
they might not have an actual statistician on board.

00:21:15.140 --> 00:21:18.900
Because I think if you think about these designs,

00:21:18.900 --> 00:21:21.859
it just screams out for basic stuff that again,

00:21:21.900 --> 00:21:24.699
I think most statisticians would know how to do.

00:21:24.699 --> 00:21:26.300
It's not hard to do them either.

00:21:27.300 --> 00:21:31.060
Python has its own like stand packages and libraries

00:21:31.060 --> 00:21:32.780
so you can do the hierarchical Bayesian model

00:21:32.780 --> 00:21:34.819
almost the same as we did it here.

00:21:35.699 --> 00:21:37.459
R for example has many, I mean,

00:21:37.459 --> 00:21:38.739
there's a lot of different packages

00:21:38.739 --> 00:21:40.699
to choose from that fit these models.

00:21:40.699 --> 00:21:43.260
So it's not like it's some arcane thing

00:21:43.260 --> 00:21:46.180
that you have to like write a dissertation to work on.

00:21:46.180 --> 00:21:49.219
It turns out to be a fairly typical design

00:21:49.219 --> 00:21:51.540
that makes it really easy to analyze.

00:21:52.420 --> 00:21:53.739
And that's pretty much it.

00:21:53.739 --> 00:21:54.780
Thanks for listening.

